1
00:00:00,290 --> 00:00:03,189
I want you to look closely at this image.

2
00:00:03,189 --> 00:00:06,540
On the left, there’s a regular candlestick
chart.

3
00:00:06,540 --> 00:00:10,730
You can see it's super noisy, with candles
bouncing all over the place.

4
00:00:10,730 --> 00:00:16,520
It's a total blur and would be very hard to
trade with so many false signals.

5
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:22,420
On the right, we have a range bar chart, tracking
the exact same price action.

6
00:00:22,420 --> 00:00:24,970
And this one is way cleaner.

7
00:00:24,970 --> 00:00:30,980
All those back-and-forth fake outs and liquidity
runs gets condensed so you can actually see

8
00:00:30,980 --> 00:00:33,540
the meaningful moves.

9
00:00:33,540 --> 00:00:36,640
There's way less noise clogging up the image.

10
00:00:36,640 --> 00:00:41,020
And it’s easier to spot which direction
the price is really going.

11
00:00:41,020 --> 00:00:46,199
On the left, trading this chart would be a
total guessing game if you don’t have exceptional

12
00:00:46,199 --> 00:00:48,110
price action skills.

13
00:00:48,110 --> 00:00:50,850
But now patterns and levels are obvious.

14
00:00:50,850 --> 00:00:58,460
Range bars strip away noise and distractions
so price behavior really stands out.

15
00:00:58,460 --> 00:01:03,949
As a day trader, it's really important that
you're always exploring new strategies and

16
00:01:03,949 --> 00:01:06,869
tweaking your approach to find an edge.

17
00:01:06,869 --> 00:01:11,600
You don't have to be afraid to try things
that aren't the most well-known.

18
00:01:11,600 --> 00:01:17,759
I was having a bad trading period, so I did
what I always do during these bad periods.

19
00:01:17,759 --> 00:01:20,850
Regroup and readjust slightly my strategy.

20
00:01:20,850 --> 00:01:23,970
And I came back to test range bars.

21
00:01:23,970 --> 00:01:30,230
Unlike candlestick or line charts that are
based on time periods, range bars only care

22
00:01:30,230 --> 00:01:32,530
about price movement.

23
00:01:32,530 --> 00:01:34,590
Time isn't a factor at all.

24
00:01:34,590 --> 00:01:41,970
At first it seemed weird not to see each candle
plotted at a certain minute or second.

25
00:01:41,970 --> 00:01:47,360
But the more I looked at it, the more I realized
range bars could be really helpful for day

26
00:01:47,360 --> 00:01:50,330
trading and scalping.

27
00:01:50,330 --> 00:01:55,820
Because day trading can seem so fast, with
a regular chart, price looks sometimes like

28
00:01:55,820 --> 00:01:59,299
a blur of lines on a small time frame.

29
00:01:59,299 --> 00:02:05,100
Range bars make it easier to spot levels where
the market may reverse or momentum could be

30
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:07,090
building.

31
00:02:07,090 --> 00:02:10,420
It takes some time getting used to reading
them at first.

32
00:02:10,420 --> 00:02:15,790
But you’ll find range bars will help you
find key areas and make entries and exits

33
00:02:15,790 --> 00:02:18,870
more obvious when markets are moving quickly.

34
00:02:18,870 --> 00:02:24,989
So when I was researching range bars, I found
out they were actually created by a Brazilian

35
00:02:24,989 --> 00:02:27,760
trader way back in the 90s.

36
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:32,970
The markets at the time were super volatile,
so he focused on developing a way to take

37
00:02:32,970 --> 00:02:35,140
advantage of that volatility.

38
00:02:35,140 --> 00:02:41,569
Since price movement mattered most in those
conditions, he wanted a chart type that centered

39
00:02:41,569 --> 00:02:44,140
on price action alone.

40
00:02:44,140 --> 00:02:49,690
That's why he designed range bars - to remove
the time factor completely.

41
00:02:49,690 --> 00:02:55,730
He felt that just looking at price was key
to understanding market volatility and different

42
00:02:55,730 --> 00:03:00,010
phases like ranging or trending.

43
00:03:00,010 --> 00:03:06,670
Normally on a chart, we see bars or candlesticks
placed at specific times, whether it's minutes

44
00:03:06,670 --> 00:03:08,010
or hours.

45
00:03:08,010 --> 00:03:12,810
But if you think about it, this could sometimes
clutter up the picture.

46
00:03:12,810 --> 00:03:18,400
The range bar idea maps out price swings without
time constraints.

47
00:03:18,400 --> 00:03:26,769
It's like a "zoomed out" view that helps identify
important areas or momentum shifts more clearly.

48
00:03:26,769 --> 00:03:31,920
From what I've seen, most trading platforms
don't have range bars available as one of

49
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:34,430
the default chart types yet.

50
00:03:34,430 --> 00:03:39,970
Luckily for us, TradingView has it for free,
as one of the standard options.

51
00:03:39,970 --> 00:03:41,939
You can find it here.

52
00:03:41,939 --> 00:03:47,290
So how do range bars actually calculate price
movements?

53
00:03:47,290 --> 00:03:53,819
Unlike normal time-based charts, each range
bar just represents a specific price change,

54
00:03:53,819 --> 00:03:55,500
not a set time period.

55
00:03:55,500 --> 00:04:00,700
We're used to charts where one candle equals
say, 30 minutes.

56
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:05,700
But with range bars, it doesn't matter how
long it took for the price to move - all that

57
00:04:05,700 --> 00:04:08,870
matters is the amount it changed.

58
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:15,159
So one bar could mean the price moved $10,
whether that happened in 10 minutes or 1 hour.

59
00:04:15,159 --> 00:04:19,989
As long as the movement was $10, that's one
range bar.

60
00:04:19,989 --> 00:04:26,460
This is different than our usual time-based
charts, which will always print the same number

61
00:04:26,460 --> 00:04:31,340
of candles each session no matter what else
is happening.

62
00:04:31,340 --> 00:04:35,000
Range bars focus only on the significant price
action.

63
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:42,570
With range bars, the number of bars you see
each session will vary a lot more than with

64
00:04:42,570 --> 00:04:44,690
normal time-based charts.

65
00:04:44,690 --> 00:04:47,919
That's one of the things that takes some adjustment.

66
00:04:47,919 --> 00:04:53,370
When volatility is high, you'll end up with
way more range bars printing.

67
00:04:53,370 --> 00:04:58,550
The price is swinging around more dramatically
in smaller increments.

68
00:04:58,550 --> 00:05:05,070
On the other hand, quieter markets with low
volatility will have fewer bars.

69
00:05:05,070 --> 00:05:11,250
Less is happening price-wise, so the bars
can remain static for longer.

70
00:05:11,250 --> 00:05:17,900
The specific market you trade and the defined
"range" you set also affect bar density.

71
00:05:17,900 --> 00:05:26,710
A $5 range on SPY will generate a different
number of bars than $5 range on OIL, for example.

72
00:05:26,710 --> 00:05:34,610
In this EURUSD example, each bar has a 10
pip range, so the high-low of each bar is

73
00:05:34,610 --> 00:05:36,530
always 10 pips.

74
00:05:36,530 --> 00:05:39,330
Then, a new bar starts.

75
00:05:39,330 --> 00:05:45,190
Essentially, range bars only care about the
total price movement - once that predefined

76
00:05:45,190 --> 00:05:50,500
threshold is hit, the bar closes and a new
one starts.

77
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:56,840
If I was watching a stock and set the range
to 10 cents, every time it moved up or down

78
00:05:56,840 --> 00:06:00,740
a total of 10 cents, a new bar would print.

79
00:06:00,740 --> 00:06:04,140
Again, time isn't a factor.

80
00:06:04,140 --> 00:06:09,330
I hope you can see how this type of chart
could give you an edge in choppy sideways

81
00:06:09,330 --> 00:06:13,990
markets or periods with very little overall
movement.

82
00:06:13,990 --> 00:06:17,639
It really isolates just the significant price
action.

83
00:06:17,639 --> 00:06:24,569
Now, when using range bars, getting the right
size for the price range is important.

84
00:06:24,569 --> 00:06:27,669
It's not a one-size-fits-all thing.

85
00:06:27,669 --> 00:06:31,000
Different markets tend to move different amounts
each day.

86
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:39,060
For example, Tesla is usually all over the
place, with daily ranges of $10-20.

87
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:44,420
Meanwhile lower priced stocks, may only move
30-40 cents.

88
00:06:44,420 --> 00:06:50,660
In general, higher priced stocks are prone
to bigger swings compared to cheaper ones.

89
00:06:50,660 --> 00:06:56,290
So if I look at Tesla using 10-cent range
bars, it wouldn't work well.

90
00:06:56,290 --> 00:06:59,720
On a lower price stock, it makes perfect sense.

91
00:06:59,720 --> 00:07:03,280
This chart looks clean and easy to analyze.

92
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:10,870
But trying to squeeze Tesla's big moves into
tiny 10-cent boxes would overload the chart

93
00:07:10,870 --> 00:07:14,160
and make it a huge messy cluster.

94
00:07:14,160 --> 00:07:19,690
And this shows how the optimal range needs
to match how volatile the market tends to

95
00:07:19,690 --> 00:07:21,580
be each day.

96
00:07:21,580 --> 00:07:26,340
Otherwise you lose the benefit of those refined
range bars.

97
00:07:26,340 --> 00:07:33,069
So when choosing a range size for bars, one
thing you can do is look at how much the market

98
00:07:33,069 --> 00:07:36,289
usually moves each day on average.

99
00:07:36,289 --> 00:07:43,400
You can see this just from experience watching
it, or use indicators like ATR to get a better

100
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:44,400
picture.

101
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:49,770
Once you know the average daily range in dollars,
you could make the bar size a percentage of

102
00:07:49,770 --> 00:07:53,560
that, like 10%, 20% or whatever you want.

103
00:07:53,560 --> 00:07:56,930
It also depends on your personal style.

104
00:07:56,930 --> 00:08:02,860
If you're a short-term scalper or day trader,
you probably want to see smaller moves, so

105
00:08:02,860 --> 00:08:05,710
a narrow range works well.

106
00:08:05,710 --> 00:08:12,009
Meanwhile, if you are a swing trader, you
need bigger ranges to highlight major swings.

107
00:08:12,009 --> 00:08:18,840
For example, let's say we’re monitoring
a market that averages 50 cent daily moves.

108
00:08:18,840 --> 00:08:21,780
You may go with a 10 cent range bar.

109
00:08:21,780 --> 00:08:26,300
This lets you focus on the quick little fluctuations
within a session.

110
00:08:26,300 --> 00:08:30,610
But a swing trader, might prefer a dollar
range bar instead.

111
00:08:30,610 --> 00:08:36,229
So I can’t tell you the perfect range bar
size that works on all markets.

112
00:08:36,229 --> 00:08:41,390
Paying attention to how you trade and how
much your markers typically move will really

113
00:08:41,390 --> 00:08:45,880
help dial in the optimal range settings.

114
00:08:45,880 --> 00:08:52,440
Range bars are really useful when viewing
how price is moving compared to normal time-based

115
00:08:52,440 --> 00:08:53,440
charts.

116
00:08:53,440 --> 00:08:59,460
On regular charts, if price is bouncing back
and forth in a small area for a while, it

117
00:08:59,460 --> 00:09:04,089
creates a bunch of messy candles that clutter
things up.

118
00:09:04,089 --> 00:09:10,670
But with range bars, all that noise gets consolidated
into just one or two bars max.

119
00:09:10,670 --> 00:09:17,690
This makes it much clearer what the actual
meaningful price action is versus small meaningless

120
00:09:17,690 --> 00:09:19,470
fluctuations.

121
00:09:19,470 --> 00:09:26,340
Since range bars won't start a new one until
the set range is hit, it filters out unimportant

122
00:09:26,340 --> 00:09:27,970
movements.

123
00:09:27,970 --> 00:09:35,010
The biggest advantage for me: areas of supply
and demand or support/resistance really pop

124
00:09:35,010 --> 00:09:38,580
out when you put horizontal lines on them.

125
00:09:38,580 --> 00:09:42,350
Trend periods and breakouts also stand out.

126
00:09:42,350 --> 00:09:48,459
I've found range bar charts to be really helpful
for scalping and day trading strategies.

127
00:09:48,459 --> 00:09:55,320
The reason is because it lets you read volatility
levels better than normal charts.

128
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:58,980
Volatility simply means how much the price
is moving around.

129
00:09:58,980 --> 00:10:05,730
On range bars, when price is trading in a
narrow sideways zone, it'll only make a few

130
00:10:05,730 --> 00:10:06,730
bars.

131
00:10:06,730 --> 00:10:08,910
This shows activity is low.

132
00:10:08,910 --> 00:10:14,810
But then if it starts to break out of that
zone as volatility increases, you can watch

133
00:10:14,810 --> 00:10:20,030
closely and notice changes in how often the
bars are printing.

134
00:10:20,030 --> 00:10:24,780
Faster bars equals more volatility from bigger
movements.

135
00:10:24,780 --> 00:10:28,300
Slower bars mean less volatility.

136
00:10:28,300 --> 00:10:35,750
Carefully observing this timing and bar frequency
over time helps spot when volatility is higher

137
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:37,430
or lower.

138
00:10:37,430 --> 00:10:44,720
And periods where it suddenly picks up usually
signal a new short term trend forming, creating

139
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:45,720
opportunities.

140
00:10:45,720 --> 00:10:52,550
Being able to see those subtle volatility
shifts is very useful for day trading.

141
00:10:52,550 --> 00:10:58,641
If you're trying to scalp the forex market
targeting let’s say 10 pips each time, then

142
00:10:58,641 --> 00:11:06,060
using a 10 pip range bar chart would definitely
make more sense compared to regular charts.

143
00:11:06,060 --> 00:11:12,510
When scalping those tiny moves, a 10 pip range
bar takes out the whole time element, which

144
00:11:12,510 --> 00:11:15,399
isn't that important at that scale.

145
00:11:15,399 --> 00:11:21,870
All that matters is seeing when the full 10
pip price swings happen regardless of how

146
00:11:21,870 --> 00:11:23,769
fast or slow it occurs.

147
00:11:23,769 --> 00:11:30,630
On a regular chart with candlesticks spaced
by time, like 5 minutes, it could take maybe

148
00:11:30,630 --> 00:11:34,570
a long time to see a single 10 pip shift.

149
00:11:34,570 --> 00:11:40,040
But the range bar would form a new box immediately
after that movement.

150
00:11:40,040 --> 00:11:46,870
Cutting out noise is key for scalping, and
range bars do that perfectly by only focusing

151
00:11:46,870 --> 00:11:54,130
on the important thresholds you're trading
around, not meaningless price wiggles in between.

152
00:11:54,130 --> 00:11:59,550
The ability to finely tune the range size
to your strategy is a big advantage over time-based

153
00:11:59,550 --> 00:12:00,550
charts.

154
00:12:00,550 --> 00:12:05,880
It really lets you zero in on exactly what
your eyes need to see to catch those small

155
00:12:05,880 --> 00:12:07,180
moves.

156
00:12:07,180 --> 00:12:13,470
Let’s me show you how I use this chart to
trade supply and demand.

157
00:12:13,470 --> 00:12:18,649
Identifying major supply and demand zones
on the charts is one of the pillars of my

158
00:12:18,649 --> 00:12:19,649
strategy.

159
00:12:19,649 --> 00:12:25,170
The first step is always looking at where
we are now price-wise.

160
00:12:25,170 --> 00:12:30,060
Then I go back on the previous day's to investigate
past swings.

161
00:12:30,060 --> 00:12:35,430
Once I spot a big move up or down, I focus
on where it started.

162
00:12:35,430 --> 00:12:41,820
That area is usually a supply or demand zone,
since that's where upside or downside pressure

163
00:12:41,820 --> 00:12:43,260
took over.

164
00:12:43,260 --> 00:12:49,830
If it was a bearish drop, I check the last
bullish range bar before the downturn.

165
00:12:49,830 --> 00:12:56,209
Then I highlight that zone up to the high
right before the move started.

166
00:12:56,209 --> 00:13:03,350
Similarly, for an upswing, I look at the most
recent bearish range bar preceding it.

167
00:13:03,350 --> 00:13:10,339
Then mark out the zone from there down to
the low preceding the start of the rally.

168
00:13:10,339 --> 00:13:16,250
When drawing supply and demand zones on range
bar charts, it's important to consider how

169
00:13:16,250 --> 00:13:18,760
"fresh" or recently used they are.

170
00:13:18,760 --> 00:13:24,420
There are a few supply and demand types:
- Fresh zones, which haven't been revisited

171
00:13:24,420 --> 00:13:27,700
yet, so they're untested.

172
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:33,540
- Non-fresh zones, which have seen price pull
back to them at least once.

173
00:13:33,540 --> 00:13:39,250
- And used up zones, which have had price
bounce off them several times.

174
00:13:39,250 --> 00:13:42,260
They're not as reliable for full swings

175
00:13:42,260 --> 00:13:47,640
When marking these on a range bar chart, focus
on:

176
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:53,279
- The freshest zones, since the market impact
is most likely still there.

177
00:13:53,279 --> 00:13:59,880
- The strongest zones, where price sharply
changed direction in a quick move.

178
00:13:59,880 --> 00:14:02,760
These command more attention.

179
00:14:02,760 --> 00:14:08,990
Paying attention to how recently zones have
been in play and how abruptly price reacted

180
00:14:08,990 --> 00:14:14,550
there can help you focus your analysis on
the most influential areas.

181
00:14:14,550 --> 00:14:19,680
Let’s look at this range bar chart, with
yesterday's price action on it.

182
00:14:19,680 --> 00:14:25,000
First step, we mark some important supply
and demand zones from how price reacted the

183
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:26,769
previous day.

184
00:14:26,769 --> 00:14:32,940
Down here near the bottom, it barely dipped
below this range before bouncing hard.

185
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:35,210
That shows strong demand.

186
00:14:35,210 --> 00:14:43,070
And up at the top, price peaked then crashed
off after struggling to break through.

187
00:14:43,070 --> 00:14:46,100
Clearly a strong supply up there.

188
00:14:46,100 --> 00:14:52,820
Now flipping to the next day, price revisited
that bottom demand area again.

189
00:14:52,820 --> 00:14:59,040
As buyers stepped up forcefully the previous
day, there’s a chance they'll protect this

190
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:00,120
level once more.

191
00:15:00,120 --> 00:15:05,589
The chart structure looks ready to turn higher
from here.

192
00:15:05,589 --> 00:15:07,690
This is your buy zone.

193
00:15:07,690 --> 00:15:13,470
Maybe it’s placebo, but I can see supply
and demand, support and resistance level more

194
00:15:13,470 --> 00:15:15,329
clearly with range bars.

195
00:15:15,329 --> 00:15:21,970
These are perfect for identifying technical
areas other traders will react at from prior

196
00:15:21,970 --> 00:15:23,190
days.

197
00:15:23,190 --> 00:15:26,199
This was just a basic intro to the concept.

198
00:15:26,199 --> 00:15:32,660
In the next videos, I want to start demonstrating
some concrete trading strategies we can actually

199
00:15:32,660 --> 00:15:35,990
apply using range bars on different markets.

200
00:15:35,990 --> 00:15:38,680
So, drop a like if you want that video.

